1
00:01:17,799 --> 00:01:19,714
Hello?

2
00:01:19,794 --> 00:01:21,544
Hello, Tom?

3
00:01:21,768 --> 00:01:27,376
Jack? Jack, it's... What, is there
a red alert on or something?

4
00:01:27,880 --> 00:01:29,744
Am I calling too late?

5
00:01:29,904 --> 00:01:33,368
No, no... It's just that the hours
are later here...

6
00:01:33,512 --> 00:01:37,665
Are you O.K.?
Is everything all right?

7
00:01:37,809 --> 00:01:39,601
Not really.

8
00:01:39,785 --> 00:01:42,450
I need some help.

9
00:01:43,777 --> 00:01:47,371
You think a speechwriter's going to fix it?
Do you think that's the only problem?

10
00:01:48,610 --> 00:01:51,042
If I did, would I be calling you?

11
00:01:51,154 --> 00:01:57,915
I'm sorry I missed your presidential
campaign. I just thought it was nuts.

12
00:01:57,978 --> 00:02:00,562
It looks like the voters agreed with you.

13
00:02:00,721 --> 00:02:06,410
Maybe it was crazy, anyway,
I'm supposed to be running again...

14
00:02:06,554 --> 00:02:11,235
<i>for the re-election to the Senate,
and people aren't giving any more.</i>

15
00:02:11,387 --> 00:02:14,098
Now, they are giving, but maybe
I just don't want the money.

16
00:02:15,642 --> 00:02:19,708
I don't have anything to say.
I feel tapped out.

17
00:02:19,923 --> 00:02:24,354
Get away from there, it's a snake pit.
It's a hall of mirrors for narcissists.

18
00:02:24,474 --> 00:02:26,218
Get a long way away.

19
00:02:26,363 --> 00:02:29,259
Oh, I wish, but it's impossible right now.

20
00:02:29,378 --> 00:02:32,409
No, come on. It's always like that.
That's always part of the problem.

21
00:02:32,578 --> 00:02:35,301
Are you offering me a place?

22
00:02:35,445 --> 00:02:37,956
Yeah, sure. You could come
over here. Come on over.

23
00:02:38,380 --> 00:02:43,550
It may not be the White House but, you
know, at least here you're wanted.

24
00:02:47,781 --> 00:02:49,686
<i>I'm so glad I came here.</i>

25
00:02:49,997 --> 00:02:53,036
<i>I should not have invited him.</i>

26
00:02:58,214 --> 00:03:00,262
Incredible!

27
00:03:00,950 --> 00:03:04,383
Look, there it is again.

28
00:03:06,463 --> 00:03:13,192
The Middle Ages got left behind on
this rock. Time just moved on.

29
00:03:14,471 --> 00:03:16,464
<i>There he goes again.
That's him all right.</i>

30
00:03:16,696 --> 00:03:20,892
<i>Always enthused and always ready,
with the right words for all occasions.</i>

31
00:03:21,119 --> 00:03:24,430
<i>As if everyone was
still waiting for his opinion.</i>

32
00:03:24,494 --> 00:03:27,469
<i>As if life itself was one
giant press conference.</i>

33
00:03:31,511 --> 00:03:36,448
<i>Maybe that's all there is,
this public persona.</i>

34
00:03:36,561 --> 00:03:40,617
<i>Maybe I've been fooling myself
these last 20 years...</i>

35
00:03:40,769 --> 00:03:44,352
<i>always looking for the real guy
behind the facade.</i>

36
00:03:44,546 --> 00:03:49,298
<i>Maybe the facade is the real guy.</i>

37
00:03:49,706 --> 00:03:52,410
This is amazing!

38
00:03:52,554 --> 00:03:56,594
<i>Sure it is.
Everything's always amazing to this guy.</i>

39
00:03:56,851 --> 00:03:58,890
<i>Why am I bitching all the time?</i>

40
00:03:59,010 --> 00:04:01,541
<i>Maybe it's a premonition that
this trip's going to be a disaster.</i>

41
00:04:01,662 --> 00:04:03,846
<i>I can't say that I need Jack's company.
This time of my life I'm residing quite...</i>

42
00:04:04,069 --> 00:04:08,434
<i>contentedly in my own midlife crises,
thank you very much.</i>

43
00:04:11,755 --> 00:04:15,406
This is as far away from Washington
as I could possibly get.

44
00:04:17,605 --> 00:04:19,955
Thank you.

45
00:04:21,300 --> 00:04:22,939
<i>There he goes.</i>

46
00:04:23,122 --> 00:04:25,652
<i>That's why he irritates me,
and that's why I love him, too.</i>

47
00:04:25,787 --> 00:04:29,498
<i>Behind the innocence there may be a
calculating politician...</i>

48
00:04:29,739 --> 00:04:32,109
<i>but behind the politician
there's an innocent.</i>

49
00:04:32,308 --> 00:04:36,373
<i>He's still american enough.
He doesn't lie well at all, he means it.</i>

50
00:04:36,581 --> 00:04:39,517
You want to stop the car and get out?
Take a look around?

51
00:04:53,294 --> 00:04:56,909
There it is.
Mont-Saint-Michel.

52
00:04:57,126 --> 00:04:58,998
What do you think?

53
00:04:59,117 --> 00:05:00,819
Beautiful.

54
00:05:02,658 --> 00:05:05,890
You want to do something different?
You want to walk over there?

55
00:05:06,907 --> 00:05:09,051
Walk across that swamp?

56
00:05:09,274 --> 00:05:13,179
Yeah, just like our ancestors did
centuries and centuries ago.

57
00:05:13,978 --> 00:05:16,907
You're the one who wanted to do all
the walking. Come on, let's go.

58
00:05:20,163 --> 00:05:22,853
Maybe you ancestors used to do this...

59
00:05:25,331 --> 00:05:28,694
but unless my mother
lied to me, I don't...

60
00:07:37,126 --> 00:07:38,327
Thank you.

61
00:07:48,125 --> 00:07:52,517
- So, we're gonna do something today?
- Thought I'd finish my book.

62
00:07:53,701 --> 00:07:56,957
You always have a book to read.
I'm bored.

63
00:07:57,344 --> 00:07:58,760
Where's Roman?

64
00:07:58,888 --> 00:08:02,520
I don't care what Roman's doing.
I wanted to do something with you.

65
00:08:05,672 --> 00:08:09,408
I should not have come. I should've
just done something with dad.

66
00:08:09,968 --> 00:08:11,704
Come on, Kit.

67
00:08:11,817 --> 00:08:15,039
You just stay cooped up in this medieval
island, just reading your books.

68
00:08:15,208 --> 00:08:18,177
You're not even aware of
what's going on around you.

69
00:08:18,266 --> 00:08:21,194
You could be anywhere, it wouldn't
even make a difference.

70
00:08:21,265 --> 00:08:23,571
You should go out more.
Meet some people.

71
00:08:23,818 --> 00:08:25,337
I will.

72
00:08:25,536 --> 00:08:27,951
I'm going.

73
00:08:28,956 --> 00:08:31,173
Bye.

74
00:08:44,549 --> 00:08:46,268
Are you moving to France permanently?

75
00:08:46,437 --> 00:08:47,381
What?

76
00:08:47,564 --> 00:08:50,141
I thought you couldn't live
anywhere but in New York.

77
00:08:54,250 --> 00:08:58,403
What about the theater?
Did you give that up for good?

78
00:08:58,490 --> 00:09:00,842
Oh, it may have given me up for good.

79
00:09:01,841 --> 00:09:06,710
I don't think I'm enough involved in
real estate to live in Manhattan...

80
00:09:06,869 --> 00:09:08,846
or any other business.
Some other hustle.

81
00:09:09,726 --> 00:09:13,044
I lived in New York when I was young inside.
My friends and I were more interested...

82
00:09:13,205 --> 00:09:15,093
in our work
than our investments.

83
00:09:15,164 --> 00:09:17,101
We weren't invidious.
We were nurturing.

84
00:09:18,477 --> 00:09:22,364
And then, you know.
Alimony, the IRS...

85
00:09:23,093 --> 00:09:26,453
being denied the right to parent
my own child custody--

86
00:09:27,318 --> 00:09:30,509
They brought reality in,
and hey, who needs it?

87
00:09:30,997 --> 00:09:35,285
When Nixon got on that chopper in 1972
I think the fight went out of all of us.

88
00:09:36,175 --> 00:09:39,318
The big business took
over and set the agenda.

89
00:09:39,950 --> 00:09:44,034
Boy, when you buy into big business,
when you buy into that, man...

90
00:09:45,123 --> 00:09:47,650
you got to emancipate
yourself from your morals...

91
00:09:47,867 --> 00:09:50,387
or you live a life of squeamishness.

92
00:09:50,539 --> 00:09:53,341
Is this our same old argument?
I lost my morals, did I?

93
00:09:53,508 --> 00:09:57,799
Automatically, by going to work
and staying inside the system?

94
00:09:58,776 --> 00:10:00,936
You're taking me a little personally.
I was talking about myself.

95
00:10:00,991 --> 00:10:03,257
I was saying that I got a little
squeamish, you know?

96
00:10:03,985 --> 00:10:08,169
I know people that work a lot crasser
jobs than you, and they're happy.

97
00:10:08,248 --> 00:10:10,721
They're happy, they're healthy,
they're not depressed.

98
00:10:10,784 --> 00:10:13,594
They enjoy the material blessings.
Me? I couldn't handle it.

99
00:10:13,672 --> 00:10:15,245
I couldn't stand it.
I just couldn't...

100
00:10:16,169 --> 00:10:21,240
Confucius say "Of the 39 steps of escape
the best one's flight." So I fled.

101
00:10:22,174 --> 00:10:24,767
Here I am in France where
I can pull down my pants.

102
00:10:25,422 --> 00:10:30,086
I'm enough of a retarded romantic to believe
France is still a place to go and think.

103
00:10:30,894 --> 00:10:36,064
So I'll stay, I guess...
or I won't. We'll see.

104
00:10:38,400 --> 00:10:40,047
This place is like a fairy tale.

105
00:10:43,871 --> 00:10:45,552
How did we wind up here?

106
00:10:46,168 --> 00:10:49,584
I'll bet there's some secret
plan of yours behind all this.

107
00:10:49,712 --> 00:10:54,761
I bet I could say the same thing about you.
No, I just thought you'd like to come here.

108
00:10:54,848 --> 00:11:00,304
To discover that precious quality that the
world so desperately lacks.

109
00:11:00,368 --> 00:11:02,889
Ah, yeah. Vision.

110
00:11:04,992 --> 00:11:09,089
Perspective.
Perspective, Jack.

111
00:11:10,398 --> 00:11:15,294
This is where the dead are placed, in the
middle of town among the houses.

112
00:11:15,458 --> 00:11:20,515
Death is a part of life, not separate from it.

113
00:11:20,763 --> 00:11:26,271
There aren't enough graves for all the
generations of Mont-Saint-Michelains.

114
00:11:26,351 --> 00:11:32,263
So every decade or so, the bones are
dug up so new bodies can be buried here.

115
00:11:32,432 --> 00:11:36,878
And since they believed you will need
your bones again on Judgment day...

116
00:11:36,989 --> 00:11:39,314
they placed them nearby
in the charnel house--

117
00:11:39,386 --> 00:11:43,131
- Ucch! That's disgusting.
- I like cemeteries.

118
00:11:43,211 --> 00:11:47,163
And in the back there, in the
church, there is a relic of a saint.

119
00:11:47,683 --> 00:11:49,046
What's a relic?

120
00:11:49,205 --> 00:11:55,611
Oh, maybe a shaving of the saint's
fingernail, or a scrap of the saint's robe.

121
00:11:55,676 --> 00:11:58,244
Tell me Jack, how do you expect
to govern these people?

122
00:11:58,276 --> 00:12:00,011
That's a good question.

123
00:12:00,763 --> 00:12:04,789
There was an italian premier
once, just before Mussolini...

124
00:12:04,877 --> 00:12:07,628
somebody asked him if it
was difficult to govern italians.

125
00:12:08,005 --> 00:12:13,317
He said: "Difficult to govern italians?
No, not difficult. Only useless"

126
00:12:14,623 --> 00:12:17,054
You didn't say that on the 6:00 news.

127
00:12:17,318 --> 00:12:23,782
No, but I thought it night and day.
Maybe that's why I lost.

128
00:12:24,919 --> 00:12:28,606
Anyway, did they really think that their
bones would keep until judgment day?

129
00:12:28,711 --> 00:12:32,039
You got to remember for them
Judgment day was...

130
00:12:32,100 --> 00:12:34,102
right around the corner.
They expected it almost hourly.

131
00:12:34,383 --> 00:12:35,566
Just like us.

132
00:12:35,743 --> 00:12:38,075
I wouldn't say so. Judgment day,
for us is different.

133
00:12:39,027 --> 00:12:44,188
It's an interruption, a violation,
a break in our concept of time--

134
00:12:44,284 --> 00:12:48,215
The bomb, the big one. Judgment day
for them was the ultimate day off.

135
00:12:48,376 --> 00:12:49,761
Not the ultimate off day.

136
00:12:50,225 --> 00:12:56,408
There wasn't mechanical time, time was
season to season, Sabbath to saint day.

137
00:12:56,601 --> 00:13:01,412
And everything led toward Judgment day.
That was the reason everybody was alive.

138
00:13:02,996 --> 00:13:07,952
It was the day of deliverance. Like sunday,
when you get the Times delivered.

139
00:13:08,241 --> 00:13:09,818
Time was sacred.

140
00:13:10,730 --> 00:13:13,170
They'd ring a bell in the morning,
they'd ring a bell in the evening...

141
00:13:13,266 --> 00:13:15,650
and those moments would
change a little. But the...

142
00:13:16,586 --> 00:13:19,479
rhythm of their era was
so different from ours...

143
00:13:19,983 --> 00:13:21,926
that I don't think we
can even imagine it.

144
00:13:32,202 --> 00:13:34,459
I guess we're a little early.

145
00:13:40,499 --> 00:13:42,835
No saint stands alone.

146
00:13:42,964 --> 00:13:44,220
What?

147
00:13:46,003 --> 00:13:48,356
No saint stands alone.

148
00:13:51,004 --> 00:13:54,284
Every time I come here, these lines
comes to me, God knows from where.

149
00:13:54,924 --> 00:13:58,444
Sometimes it takes me weeks, even
years to figure out what they mean.

150
00:13:58,915 --> 00:14:02,125
Did you ever read any
of the books I sent you?

151
00:14:02,605 --> 00:14:07,381
No, not since you stopped thinking
about helping me with speeches.

152
00:14:08,342 --> 00:14:11,117
Did you ever read the
speeches I sent you?

153
00:14:11,253 --> 00:14:14,838
I tried. I mean, the old attention span,
isn't what it used to be.

154
00:14:15,069 --> 00:14:17,566
That's true. Mine neither.

155
00:14:18,902 --> 00:14:22,094
I don't have any attention anymore
for anything that's not specific.

156
00:14:23,125 --> 00:14:25,492
Poetry just confuses me.

157
00:14:25,677 --> 00:14:28,332
Yeah, politics--
Politics confuses everybody.

158
00:14:29,028 --> 00:14:31,487
Including its practitioners.

159
00:14:32,838 --> 00:14:35,511
But I know what
"No saint stands alone" means.

160
00:14:35,870 --> 00:14:37,759
Oh, yeah? What?

161
00:14:37,935 --> 00:14:40,135
It's the essence of my profession.

162
00:14:40,351 --> 00:14:45,183
Because between every politician
and his own point of view...

163
00:14:45,344 --> 00:14:49,806
there's always three fat cats, two
pac lobbyists, half dozen of microphones.

164
00:14:50,774 --> 00:14:54,959
"No man is an island entire of itself.
Every man is a piece of the continent...

165
00:14:55,023 --> 00:14:59,252
part of the main, therefore never send
to know for whom the bell tolls...

166
00:14:59,281 --> 00:15:01,793
it tolls to thee."

167
00:15:12,360 --> 00:15:14,783
Can't you just feel the
place watching you?

168
00:15:16,184 --> 00:15:21,304
- It makes you feel pretty small.
- It was supposed to.

169
00:15:21,551 --> 00:15:25,184
The individual in the human body was
supposed to feel small...

170
00:15:25,366 --> 00:15:27,703
dwarfed, denied all independent existence.

171
00:15:31,464 --> 00:15:36,929
We lost some of the sense of being
all one, but we got our freedom.

172
00:15:37,089 --> 00:15:39,176
That's not a bad trade-off.

173
00:15:39,588 --> 00:15:44,261
I don't know. I still don't know if we
haven't lost more than we've gained.

174
00:15:44,493 --> 00:15:47,157
All I ever hear anybody
talk about today is themselves.

175
00:15:47,269 --> 00:15:52,782
I wrote a poem once. It's titled
"The Stones Speak, I am Silent"

176
00:15:52,785 --> 00:15:57,350
At least you're free to think what
you want and do what you can about it.

177
00:15:58,252 --> 00:16:01,285
Think of the guy who had to carry these
stones up the hell to built this place.

178
00:16:01,438 --> 00:16:05,438
He didn't have any say in life,
or try running for office some day.

179
00:16:06,926 --> 00:16:10,070
Someone else sets the agenda,
someone else sets the schedule.

180
00:16:10,238 --> 00:16:13,541
Somebody else decides what you can
say and what you better not say.

181
00:16:14,374 --> 00:16:19,422
Talk about losing yourself. People have
been known to forget their own names.

182
00:16:20,415 --> 00:16:22,141
Maybe you're too smart to be president.

183
00:16:22,349 --> 00:16:25,013
A television correspondent
told me that once.

184
00:16:25,123 --> 00:16:26,372
What did you say?

185
00:16:26,470 --> 00:16:28,869
I got a little steamed.

186
00:16:29,750 --> 00:16:33,638
I said american voters want their
leaders to be dumber than they are.

187
00:16:33,741 --> 00:16:38,949
They figure they'll do less harm that way.
That is an expensive form of cynicism.

188
00:16:39,838 --> 00:16:41,807
- You said that on TV?
- Yup.

189
00:16:42,862 --> 00:16:45,182
Maybe you're not so smart after all.

190
00:16:53,130 --> 00:16:54,897
We go through here.

191
00:16:57,978 --> 00:16:59,225
What's up here?

192
00:16:59,465 --> 00:17:01,106
After you.

193
00:17:17,072 --> 00:17:19,383
Look at this.
Look at this!

194
00:17:19,551 --> 00:17:22,048
This thing has been functioning
for hundreds of years--

195
00:17:22,232 --> 00:17:24,152
since before the
beginning of modern times.

196
00:17:24,296 --> 00:17:27,497
But this is different from the kind
of time you were talking about before.

197
00:17:27,673 --> 00:17:30,617
Sunrise to Sunset,
Sabbath to Sabbath, isn't it?

198
00:17:30,762 --> 00:17:34,593
This is... mechanical time.

199
00:17:34,720 --> 00:17:36,417
You bet, you bet it is.

200
00:17:36,561 --> 00:17:39,689
I sometimes think that this clock,
this machine is what...

201
00:17:39,825 --> 00:17:42,802
...constitutes humanity's first real
break from the world of nature.

202
00:17:43,827 --> 00:17:46,699
Wouldn't you say so?
Hello?

203
00:17:46,843 --> 00:17:50,890
The clock did much more than that.
It became the model of the cosmos.

204
00:17:50,954 --> 00:17:53,707
And then they mistook the
model for the real thing.

205
00:17:54,091 --> 00:17:57,551
People got the idea that
nature was just a giant clock.

206
00:17:57,696 --> 00:18:00,451
Not a living organism, but a machine.

207
00:18:01,306 --> 00:18:05,223
That's exactly what I've been trying to
tell this lunkhead, exactly, word for word.

208
00:18:05,328 --> 00:18:07,806
- What?
- Maybe you recognize him. Jack Edwards.

209
00:18:07,910 --> 00:18:09,545
And you are...?

210
00:18:09,810 --> 00:18:14,900
Sonia Hoffman.
I think I've heard your name somewhere.

211
00:18:15,052 --> 00:18:17,301
Maybe in a couple of
hundred news broadcasts.

212
00:18:17,461 --> 00:18:20,052
He was a candidate for the U.S.
presidency in the primaries.

213
00:18:20,229 --> 00:18:24,348
I vaguely remember.
See? I'm not a voter.

214
00:18:24,523 --> 00:18:26,909
Most americans don't vote either.

215
00:18:29,072 --> 00:18:30,601
I do know who you are.

216
00:18:30,745 --> 00:18:31,914
Me? You know who I am?
I doubt it...

217
00:18:32,889 --> 00:18:34,491
You're Thomas Harriman, the poet.

218
00:18:36,243 --> 00:18:39,507
Yes I am. But wait a minute,
let me get this straight.

219
00:18:39,636 --> 00:18:43,382
You recognize me, a poet whose latest
work sold only 12,000 copies but you...

220
00:18:43,541 --> 00:18:49,389
do not recognize this gentleman, who
was a presidential candidate in America?

221
00:18:49,502 --> 00:18:52,694
My god, woman. What's happened to
your values? What do you do?

222
00:18:52,821 --> 00:18:54,589
I'm a scientist.

223
00:18:54,726 --> 00:18:57,494
And we do occasionally read poetry.

224
00:18:57,614 --> 00:19:00,167
As a matter of fact, I'm doing
a lot of it these days.

225
00:19:00,270 --> 00:19:01,959
I'm on a sort of sabbatical.

226
00:19:02,742 --> 00:19:06,959
I'm an ex-physicist,
an ex-american resident...

227
00:19:07,080 --> 00:19:08,783
- an ex-voter--
- Ex-wife?

